                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d244">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/400a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reinsch</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-06T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 6, 1915—6 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The President desires that you call upon the Foreign Office and urge that the
                    negotiations between China and Japan shall be conducted in a spirit of patience
                    and friendliness, and be continued until an amicable solution of the existing
                    disputes is found. China and Japan, because of their geographical position must
                    remain neighbors and because of their mutual interests must be friends. It would
                    be most unfortunate if they should be brought into armed conflict, especially at
                    this time when so large a portion of the world is at war. Peaceful means are
                    urged in the conviction that they will, in the end, prove best for both China
                    and Japan and for the rest of the world as well.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
